Exercise 1

We might note that we are dealing with an AR(1) process with slope \(0.9\) and, assuming a central requirement, central \(t\) - distributed noise with ten degrees of freedom. We simulate noise terms \(Z_t\) for \(t=1,\ldots,1000\)

set.seed(314)
desiredlag <- 20
phi <- 0.9
n <- 10^3
Z <- rt(df = 10, n=n)

As such we may simulate the AR(1) process using the update scheme defining the stopped AR(1) process

X <- rep(NA,n)
X[1] <- Z[1]
for (j in 2:n) {
   X[j] <- phi*X[j-1]+Z[j]
}
ts.plot(X)

We plot the acf confidence bands:

acf(X, lag.max = desiredlag, plot = T)

#acf(X, lag.max = desiredlag, plot = F)

Assuming the requirement to sample from \(X,\) and not from \(Z\) which would be more in line with the theoretical foundation for permutations of data, which are in and of themselves understood here, to be a random reordering of all data points. We may create a matrix containing \(10^3\) rows, each a permutation of the \(X\) data as such:

m <- 10^3
M <- matrix(NA, nrow = m, ncol = n)
for (i in 1:m) {
   M[i,] <- sample(X)
}

For each of these permuted data sets, we will use acf to calculate sample autocorrelations for lags once again up to desiredlag =\(20,\) and then the \(95\%\) quantiles for each of the lags:

AutM <- apply(M,1,acf,lag.max=desiredlag, plot = F)
temp <- matrix(NA,nrow = m, ncol = desiredlag+1)

b)

We note that our AR(1) model is causal as \(\mathopen{}\left|{\phi}\right|\mathclose{}<1.\) Following example 4.25, we will need to calculate the sample autocovariance function: \[\begin{equation*} \gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({h}\right)\mathclose{}:=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{t=1}^{n-h}{\mathopen{}\left({X_t-\overline{X}_n}\right)\mathclose{}\mathopen{}\left({X_{t+h}-\overline{X}_n}\right)\mathclose{}} \end{equation*}\] and autocorrelation function: \[\begin{equation*} \rho_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({h}\right)\mathclose{}:=\frac{\gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({h}\right)\mathclose{}}{\gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({0}\right)\mathclose{}} \end{equation*}\] Note thus in particular that we may calculate \(\gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({1}\right)\mathclose{},\,\gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({0}\right)\mathclose{}\) in with the following homemade function

gammaf <- function(X,h) {
   n <- length(X)
   gamt <- 0
   for (t in 1:(n-h)) {
      tempt <- (X[t]-mean(X))*(X[t+h]-mean(X)) 
      gamt <- gamt + tempt
   }
   1/n*gamt
}

Yielding

gammaf(X,1)
## [1] 5.640264
gammaf(X,0)
## [1] 6.317588

Such that for

\[ \hat{\phi}_n=\frac{\gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({1}\right)\mathclose{}}{\gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({0}\right)\mathclose{}}\equiv\rho_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({1}\right)\mathclose{} \] \[ \hat{\sigma}_n^2=\gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({0}\right)\mathclose{}\mathopen{}\left({1-\rho_{n,X}^2\mathopen{}\left({1}\right)\mathclose{}}\right)\mathclose{} \]

(rho1 <- gammaf(X,1)/gammaf(X,0))
## [1] 0.8927876
(phih <- rho1)
## [1] 0.8927876
(sigmah2 <- gammaf(X,0)*(1-rho1^2))
## [1] 1.28203

Let \(\nu=10\) be the degrees of freedom of our student-t distributed random noise \(Z_t.\) As is surmised on page 47-48 in the lecture notes, in dealing with a causal AR(1) process driven by iid noise \(Z_t\) with variance \(\sigma^2=\frac{\nu}{\nu-2}=\frac{10}{8}=\frac{5}{4},\) we have asymptotic normality of \(\hat\phi\) with corresponding asymptotic mean \(\phi\) and asymptotic variance \(\frac{\sigma^2\Gamma_p^{-1}}{n}\) i.e. \[ \hat\phi_n\overset{\textit{as}}{\sim}\mathcal{N}\mathopen{}\left({{\phi},{\frac{\sigma^2\Gamma_{p=1}^{-1}}{n}}}\right)\mathclose{} \] or equivalently \[ \sqrt{n}\mathopen{}\left({\hat\phi-\phi}\right)\mathclose{}\overset{\textit{d}}{\rightarrow}\mathcal{N}\mathopen{}\left({{0},{\sigma^2\Gamma_{1}^{-1}}}\right)\mathclose{}. \] With this we may for our fixed \(n=1000\) determine that \(\mathopen{}\left({\phi - \frac{1.96}{\sqrt{n}}\sqrt{\sigma^2\Gamma_1^{-1}},\,\phi + \frac{1.96}{\sqrt{n}}\sqrt{\sigma^2\Gamma_1^{-1}}}\right)\mathclose{}\) will be an asymptotic \(95\%\) confidence interval for \(\phi.\) Estimating \(\Gamma_1\) via the sample autocovariance function, we find: \[ \tilde\Gamma_1:=\gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({1-1}\right)\mathclose{}=\gamma_{n,X}\mathopen{}\left({0}\right)\mathclose{}=6.3175881 \] such that \[ \tilde\Gamma_1^{-1}=\frac{1}{\tilde\Gamma_1}=0.1582883\neq0 \] such that we may rewrite the confidence bands as \[ \mathopen{}\left({\phi - \frac{1.96}{\sqrt{n}}\sqrt{\sigma^20.1582883},\,\phi + \frac{1.96}{\sqrt{n}}\sqrt{\sigma^20.1582883}}\right)\mathclose{} \] Inserting the other estimates and \(n=1000\) we get \[\begin{equation*} \mathopen{}\left({\hat\phi - \frac{1.96}{\sqrt{10^3}}\sqrt{\hat\sigma^20.1582883},\,\hat\phi + \frac{1.96}{\sqrt{10^3}}\sqrt{\hat\sigma^20.1582883}}\right)\mathclose{}\\ =\mathopen{}\left({0.8927876 - \frac{1.96}{\sqrt{10^3}}\sqrt{0.2029302},\,0.8927876 + \frac{1.96}{\sqrt{10^3}}\sqrt{0.2029302}}\right)\mathclose{}\\ =\mathopen{}\left({0.8648667,0.9207085}\right)\mathclose{} \end{equation*}\]

part2)

We repeat the tasks done in the previous exercises by writing a function to do so

boots <- function(Zh,n) { #Simulating the Bootstrap data
   q <- length(Zh)
   XhsM <- matrix(NA,nrow=n,ncol=q)
   for (i in 1:n) {
      Zhsi <- sample(Zh)
      XhsM[i,1] <- Zhsi[1]
      for (j in 2:q) {
        XhsM[i,j] <- phih*XhsM[i,j-1]+Zhsi[j]
      }
   }
   XhsM
}

dat <- boots(Zh,1000)
YW <- function(Zh,n) { #Calculating the YW's
   q <- length(Zh)
   dat <- boots(Zh,n)
   phihV <- rep(NA,n)
   for (i in 1:n) {
      phihV[i] <- gammaf(dat[i,],1)/gammaf(dat[i,],0)
   }
   phihV
}
phihV <- YW(Zh,n)
hist(phihV)

boxplot(phihV)

quantile(phihV, c(0.025, 0.975))
##      2.5%     97.5% 
## 0.8587749 0.9149991

rbind(quantile(phihV, c(0.025, 0.975)), c(phih - 1.96/(sqrt(n))*sqrt(sigmah2*1/gammaf(X,0)),phih + 1.96/(sqrt(n))*sqrt(sigmah2*1/gammaf(X,0))))
##           2.5%     97.5%
## [1,] 0.8587749 0.9149991
## [2,] 0.8648667 0.9207085

we notice a great similarity, though the asymptotic confidence interval seems shifted approximately \(\cong0.007\) in comparison to the bootstrap interval.

Exercise 4

a)

Noting that \(\rho_X\mathopen{}\left({h}\right)\mathclose{}=\phi^{\mathopen{}\left|{h}\right|\mathclose{}}\) we may compute \[\begin{align} w_{hh}&=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}{\mathopen{}\left({\rho_X\mathopen{}\left({k+h}\right)\mathclose{}+\rho_X\mathopen{}\left({k-h}\right)\mathclose{}-2\rho_X\mathopen{}\left({h}\right)\mathclose{}\rho_X\mathopen{}\left({k}\right)\mathclose{}}\right)\mathclose{}^2}\\ &=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}{\mathopen{}\left({\phi^{\mathopen{}\left|{k+h}\right|\mathclose{}}+\phi^{\mathopen{}\left|{k-h}\right|\mathclose{}}-\phi^{\mathopen{}\left|{k}\right|\mathclose{}}\phi^{\mathopen{}\left|{h}\right|\mathclose{}}}\right)\mathclose{}^2}\\ &=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}{\mathopen{}\left({\phi^{\mathopen{}\left|{k-h}\right|\mathclose{}}-\phi^{\mathopen{}\left|{k+h}\right|\mathclose{}}}\right)\mathclose{}^2}\\ &=\sum_{k=1}^{h}{\mathopen{}\left({\phi^{h-k}-\phi^{k+h}}\right)\mathclose{}^2}+\sum_{k=h+1}^{\infty}{\mathopen{}\left({\phi^{k-h}-\phi^{k+h}}\right)\mathclose{}^2}\\ &=\sum_{k=1}^{h}{\phi^{2h}\mathopen{}\left({\phi^{-k}-\phi^{k}}\right)\mathclose{}^2}+\sum_{k=h+1}^{\infty}{\phi^{2k}\mathopen{}\left({\phi^{-h}-\phi^{h}}\right)\mathclose{}^2}\\ &=\phi^{2h}\sum_{k=1}^{h}{\mathopen{}\left({\phi^{-k}-\phi^{k}}\right)\mathclose{}^2}+\mathopen{}\left({\phi^{-h}-\phi^{h}}\right)\mathclose{}^2\sum_{k=h+1}^{\infty}{\phi^{2k}}\\ &=-\frac{\phi^{2h}\mathopen{}\left({1+2h - \phi^2-2h \phi^2 - \phi^{-2h}+\phi^{2+2h}}\right)\mathclose{}}{1-\phi^2}+\frac{\phi^{2h+2}\mathopen{}\left({\phi^{-h}-\phi^h}\right)\mathclose{}^2}{1-\phi^2} \end{align}\] such that for \(0<\phi<1\) we may conclude that for \(h\rightarrow\infty\) \[\begin{align} w_{hh}\rightarrow\frac{1}{1-\phi^2}+\frac{\phi^2}{1-\phi^2}. \end{align}\]

b)

We will simulate a size \(200\) sample from the AR(1) process as follows:

sim4b <- arima.sim(model = list(ar = 0.8), n=200)
ts.plot(sim4b)

We may draw the sample auotcorrelations, along with the confidence band for the iid white noise for a \(25\) lag:

acf(sim4b, lag.max = 25)

for each lag up to \(25\) we may do the calculation of the \(95\%\) asymptotic confidence bands from a)

n4b <- 200
phi4b <- 0.8
rhonX4b <- as.numeric(acf(sim4b, lag.max = 25, plot=F)[[1]])
w <- 1:25
autocorconfp <- 1:25
autocorconfm <- 1:25
for (h in w) {
   w[h] <- -((phi4b^(2*h))*(1+2*h-phi4b^2-2*h*phi4b^2-phi4b^(-2*h)+phi4b^(2+2*h)))/(1-phi4b^2)+(phi4b^(2*h+2)*(phi4b^(-h)-phi4b^h)^2)/(1-phi4b^2)
   autocorconfp[h] <- rhonX4b[h]+qnorm(0.975)*sqrt(w[h]/n4b)
   autocorconfm[h] <- rhonX4b[h]-qnorm(0.975)*sqrt(w[h]/n4b)
}
autocorconf <- rbind(autocorconfp, autocorconfm)

We may plot the asymptotic correlation confidence bands together with the previous sample auto correlation function

acf(sim4b, lag.max = 25, ylim = c(-1,1));lines(1:25, autocorconfp, lty = 3);lines(1:25, autocorconfm, lty = 3)
